image.altText: Aboriginal men with spears dance around a table with a cross on it and a box of ashes

props.synopsis: The remains of a Warlpiri ancestor have been returned to country near Yuendumu in the Northern Territory this week. It comes 60 years after the body was exhumed by station owners.

title.children: Remains of 'King of the Warlpiri' returned to sacred country near Yuendumu

image.altText: Michelle Bullock speaks at a podium with branding behind her. She is gesturing with her hand.

props.synopsis: Inflation falls faster than expected in October, taking some pressure off the RBA to back up this month's interest rate rise with another before Christmas.

title.children: RBA boss says rate rises have 'created a lot of noise' but most Australians 'are actually in a pretty good position'

image.altText: Brittany Higgins outside court surrounded by media.

props.synopsis: Brittany Higgins tells the Federal Court she was the most intoxicated she had ever been on the night in question.

title.children: Brittany Higgins details alleged rape as she takes the stand in Bruce Lehrmann's defamation action

image.altText: A woman peers to the side in front of a window wearing a black shirt

props.synopsis: As survivors of alleged historical physical and sexual abuse at the hands of foster carers in the Northern Territory seek justice, they say they are battling significant delays and distress akin to "being abused again".

title.children: Mary was repeatedly abused as a child in the foster care system. She's among dozens of survivors battling for justice

image.altText: Indigenous man with grey hair stands in front of an old mine site which hasn't been cleaned up

props.synopsis: Labelled 'one of the worst polluting mines in Australia', the Redbank Mine has been leaking acid into the environment for almost 30 years. Now traditional owners are calling for it to be rehabilitated before any more new mines are opened in the NT.

title.children: 'Like a scene out of Mad Max': Indigenous leaders call for urgent rehabilitation of toxic former copper mine

image.altText: A white sign with red writing reads: Barkly Region Alcohol and Drug Abuse Advisory Group.

props.synopsis: The organisation's chair accuses the Northern Territory government of "institutionalised racism" over its failure to progress the construction of a new residential rehabilitation facility more than five years after it was green-lit.

title.children: Remote NT rehab clinic threatens to lodge human rights complaint over delays in new facility

image.altText: Jeremy Buckingham in a blazer, shirt and glasses holding  green cannabis in his hand

props.synopsis: Jeremy Buckingham produced a 'bud' of medicinal cannabis in NSW parliament on Wednesday, which he said he obtained with a prescription.

title.children: 'What's to be afraid of?': Cannabis stunt pulled in NSW parliament during legalisation bill bid

image.altText: Drone captures scale of Lake Conjola flooding

props.synopsis: Residents in a South Coast town say the water level has risen by more than a metre since last night and more extreme weather is forecast for today as authorities scramble to respond to emergencies around the state.

title.children: Homes inundated, power outages and rescues amid widespread flooding in NSW

image.altText: Hands take Australian money notes out of a wallet.

props.synopsis: An average of $240 is waiting to be claimed by nearly a million Australians who have out-of-date or unrecorded bank details with Medicare.

title.children: Nearly 1 million Australians have unclaimed Medicare benefits waiting for them

image.altText: Australian Tax Office

props.synopsis: The tax office has stopped sending letters warning of sometimes decades-old tax debts, acknowledging the letters were causing "unnecessary distress".

title.children: Australian Tax Office's robodebt-like tax debt recovery scheme under review

image.altText: A man in a hat stands at a lectern

props.synopsis: The federal Member for Calare, Andrew Gee, has told parliament a package containing an "insulting" and "threatening" message was delivered to his home last week, with the alleged sender admitting it "when confronted by police".

title.children: Nationals take action against official after MP accuses her of 'nasty' delivery to his home

image.altText: An older Aboriginal man wearing a suit and wide brimmed hat walks with two Indigenous women on either side of him.

props.synopsis: Pat Dodson's departure from parliament will leave a cavernous hole in Canberra, as he takes with him a dignified approach to diplomacy and a lifetime of hard-won battles in the fight for his mob, writes Bridget Brennan.

title.children: Whatever the debate, Pat Dodson had the same reminder for journalists: Study Australia's history

image.altText: A supercell over Queensland

props.synopsis: Supercells are the biggest and baddest kind of severe thunderstorm, capable of producing violent winds, large hail, and tornadoes.

title.children: Eastern Australia rolling in storms and wild weather, including the most dangerous – supercell thunderstorms

image.altText: A group of Indian miners.

props.synopsis: Indian workers are greeted with wild cheers and flower garlands as rescuers safely brought out all 41 from the collapsed Himalayan road tunnel where they were trapped for 17 days.

title.children: 'We got a new life': India jubilant as trapped workers rescued from Himalayan tunnel

image.altText: a man with brown facial hair leaning against a row of wine bottles

props.synopsis: Multiple takeaway liquor outlets in Darwin say they were surprised to find out the hours they could operate would be cut by two hours per day after the government's announcement, by a press release and media.

title.children: Amid rising crime rates, Darwin liquor outlets discover via media their opening hours are to be slashed

image.altText: A young person holding a small dog and standing outside between two armed men wearing balaclavas, standing near cars.

props.synopsis: For the first time since the truce began, both sides of the war trade accusations of serious ceasefire violations. Follow live.

title.children: Israel and Hamas trade ceasefire accusations as more prisoners and hostages are released

liveBlogKeyEvents.title: Labor delegation calls on federal MPs to advocate for ceasefire
168 Palestinians detained in West Bank during truce: Palestinian Prisoner's Society
Talks for longer ceasefire and preparations for more hostage swaps underway

image.altText: Anthony Albanese looks at Clare O'Neil during question time

props.synopsis: It's hard to see how the fallout from a landmark High Court ruling on indefinite immigration detention can be described as anything other than potty, with politicians rushing around like chooks with their heads cut off.

title.children: The questionable High Court advice that could have prevented a whole lot of Labor pains

image.altText: A man with grey hair wearing a black suit and purple tie.

props.synopsis: Paul Charlton, 69, is sentenced to 24 years behind bars for the 2007 murder of his girlfriend Joanne Howell, which he tried to blame on an intruder.

title.children: Paul Charlton sentenced to 24 years' jail for 2007 murder of Melbourne singer Joanne Howell

image.altText: Missing woman Jessica Zrinski smiling while sat in a car

props.synopsis: CCTV footage shows the last sighting of Jessica Zrinski in a blue Holden Commodore with a man she had just met. Twelve months on, her desperate family are still looking for answers.

title.children: Sydney woman was last seen getting into a stranger's car. Twelve months later he's refusing to talk to police

image.altText: Detectives standing around police cars

props.synopsis: Police say officers were called to a home on Tuesday afternoon following reports an 88-year-old man had been found dead, and were then called back again on Wednesday morning after a 63-year-old man was found dead.

title.children: Police investigating suspected murder-suicide after two men found dead at Adelaide home

image.altText: Tiny Pinder

props.synopsis: An ABC investigation finds authorities missed multiple opportunities to deport an NBL player and serial rapist, despite him sexually abusing and stalking multiple women and girls in Australia.

title.children: He's a serial sexual predator who is no longer an Australian citizen. So why hasn't Tiny Pinder been deported?

image.altText: Jimmy Carter in a wheel chair with a blanket over his lap.

props.synopsis: Rosalynn Carter was remembered as the glue that held the family together at the service attended by former presidents and first ladies.

title.children: Jimmy Carter, 99, makes rare public appearance at his wife Rosalynn's memorial

image.altText: A man in a green army jacket sits in a wheelchair in a clearing in a wood

props.synopsis: An officer who led his troops into one of the key initial battles of Ukraine's counteroffensive labels the operation a failure.

title.children: This Ukrainian commander says leaks, fearsome choppers and poor planning doomed the counteroffensive

image.altText: A bright yellow tree in a burnt out paddock

props.synopsis: Bright yellow flowers on an ancient tree have been a warning sign of impending bushfires for thousands of years, Aboriginal people on the WA south coast say, and it comes with fireys already fatigued from fighting big blazes.

title.children: West Australian Christmas 'fire tree' signals an early threat

image.altText: A generic undated stock photo showing a map of Australia with heaps of pins stuck in it.

props.synopsis: While it's probably no surprise that governments spent billions of dollars fighting COVID-19, new data analysis shows how much Australians spent during the first three years of the pandemic.

title.children: How did Australia's COVID strategy compare to other countries? New data paints a striking picture

image.altText: Western whipbirds recently photographed

props.synopsis: Wildlife experts are surprised to see some bird species re-emerge across Kangaroo Island after the devastating bushfires in 2019-2020.

title.children: Experts surprised to find endangered bird species in animal refuge grounds

image.altText: A sunset over the river.

props.synopsis: The Commonwealth will have a green light to enter the water market and buy irrigation water from farmers to boost the environment, with the Albanese government securing the numbers to re-write the Murray-Darling Basin Plan.

title.children: $50 million river deal to green-light environmental water buybacks

image.altText: A blurred photo of the share trading boards at the Australian stock exchange

props.synopsis: Falling monthly inflation figures cut rate rise bets and sent shares higher, as the RBA governor presented an upbeat picture of household finances — as it happened.

title.children: ASX gains as falling inflation lowers pre-Christmas rate rise risks — as it happened

image.altText: Front view of unidentified youth.

props.synopsis: Tasmania's commissioner for children and young people says allocating adolescents in out-of-home care a case management team instead of an individual case manager violated their rights to feel safe, to be treated with respect, and to have safe contact with their families.

title.children: Commissioner finds children's rights violated by out-of-home care model

image.altText: A man looks straight ahead with green tinted sunglasses on

props.synopsis: Clare Nowland, who had dementia, died in Cooma Hospital in May a week after allegedly being tasered by Senior Constable Kristian White at her Yallambee Lodge nursing home.

title.children: NSW police officer charged with manslaughter over fatal tasering of Clare Nowland

image.altText: A group of people hold flashlights with their hands in the air.

props.synopsis: Qatar says it is working with both sides to try and further extend the temporary ceasefire between Hamas and Israel.

title.children: Temporary ceasefire between Israel and Hamas could be further extended
